## Lightning layout

- Lightning does **not** use CSS. All positioning via `x`, `y`, `width`, `height` properties on nodes — **absolute positioning by default**.
- Lightning's built-in `display: "flex"` is a lightweight engine in the renderer, **not** browser CSS flex. Acceptable for simple row/column containers.
- **Agent rule:** When generating Lightning/SolidTV UI code, use Lightning node properties (`x`, `y`, `w`, `h`, `color`, `borderRadius`, etc.) — **never** CSS classes, `style={{}}`, or DOM elements. See [AI Coding Guidelines](https://github.com/lightning-tv/solid/blob/main/docs/AI_CODING_GUIDELINES.md).

### Lightning styling rules

- Colors: hex strings (`"#ff0000ff"`). No named colors.
- No `background` — use `color`.
- Borders: `border={{ width: 1, color: "#000000ff" }}`. No CSS strings.
- `borderRadius`: number or array `[tl, tr, br, bl]`.
- No CSS classes, no `style={{}}`, no `className`.
- Padding: single `padding` number only (no directional padding).
- Margins: `marginTop`, `marginBottom`, `marginLeft`, `marginRight`.

---

## Runtime scaling (Lightning)

- Design at **1920×1080**. Set **Lightning's scale property** at runtime to adapt to device resolution (e.g. 1280×720).
- Author all layout values as whole numbers in 1920×1080 space. Lightning handles conversion.
- No `px()` utility needed — Lightning scaling does it at the renderer level.

---

## Performance (Lightning-specific)

- Lightning targets **WebGL on constrained TV hardware** (10-100x slower than phones).
- **Lazy/virtualized lists:** Only create/mount nodes for items on or near screen. Use `<For>`, `<Show>`, signals, `Virtual` / `VirtualGrid` to control which nodes exist. Target 8-15 active elements, not 100+.
- **Minimal first scene.** Defer heavy textures and non-critical components after first frame.
- **Batch model updates.** Avoid synchronous large transforms in the same tick as input handling.
- **Component pooling:** Recycle Lightning nodes by updating properties (text, texture src, color) rather than removing and re-creating `<View>` / `<Text>`.

### Texture memory (experimental)

Lightning 3 manages texture cache internally. Manual `texture.free()` vs renderer eviction is not settled. **Agent rule:** Prompt developer to test both when near memory ceiling.
